Demosthenes pro Ctesiphonte festinatum ait a Philippo, ut quae posset loca occuparet, gnarus ut res erat, pacis confecto negotio, retenturum se quae teneret. Incorpo- ralia non tenentur nisi per res, quibus adhaerent, ut servitutes praediorum, aut per personas quarum sunt, dum ne in solo quod hostium fuit exercenda sint.

XIII. In altero illo paciscendi genere, quo restituitur possessio bello turbata, notandum est, ultimam, quae ante bel- lum fuit, possessionem respici, ita tamen ut privatis deiectis interdicto aut vindicatione apud judicem experiri liceat.

XIV. At si quis sui juris populus sponte se bellantium alteri subjecerit, ad eum restitutio non porrigetur, ut quae ad ea tantum pertineat, quae vi, metu facta sunt, aut alioqui et dolo non nisi in hostem licito. Sic pace inter Graecos The- bani iPlataeam retinuerunt, dicentes: οὗ βίᾳ ἀλλ’ ὁμολογίᾳ αὐτῶν προσχωρησάντων, καὶ οὑ προδόντων, ἔχειν τὸ χωρίον · habere se cum locum non vi, non proditione, sed eorum quorum erat libera voluntate. Demosthenes says that Philip made haste to occupy what places he could, knowing that when peace was made, he would keep what he held. Incorporeal possessions are not held, except by means of the thing to which they adhere3 as the servitudes of lands3 or by the persons to whom they belong, provided they are not such as are to be exereised in the soil which had been the enemy's3 [for then they go with the soil].

XIII. In the other kind of pacification, the status quo ante bellum, it is to be noted that the last possession which preceded the war is meant3 but in such a way, that private encroachments are to be sot aside by an order of court, or sentence of a judge, when it can beliad.

XIV. But if any people, which is its own master, has, of its own free will,subjeeted itself to one of the belligerent parties, the restitu- tionis not to be extended to it, since the restitution applies to those things which are done by soree or sear, or by some stratagem lawful towards an enemy. So when the Greeks made peace, the Thebans retained Plataea3 saying, that they had azot taken it bysome, ‘nor by trea- chery, but by the free will of those whose it was· And on the like grounds, Niseca remained in the possession of the Athenin-ns, T.
